name: Housing New York Units by Building
attribution: Department of Housing Preservation and Development (HPD)
description: The Department of Housing Preservation and Development (HPD) reports on buildings, units, and projects that began after January 1, 2014 and are counted towards the Housing New York plan. The Housing New York Units by Building file presents this data by building, and includes building-level data, such as house number, street name, BBL, and BIN for each building in a project.  The unit counts are provided by building. For additional documentation, including a data dictionary, review the attachments in the “About this Dataset” section of the Primer landing page.

columns.name: Project ID
columns.description: The Project ID is a unique numeric identifier assigned to each project by HPD.

columns.name: Project Name
columns.description: The Project Name is the name assigned to the project by HPD.

columns.name: Program Group
columns.description: The broadened program category for a project, which is based on the project’s primary program. See table below labeled “Program Group Definitions” for more information.

columns.name: Project Start Date
columns.description: The Project Start Date is the date of the project loan or agreement closing.

columns.name: Project Completion Date
columns.description: The Project Completion Date is the date that the last building in the project was completed. If the project has not yet completed, then the field is blank.

columns.name: Building ID
columns.description: The Building ID is a unique numeric identifier assigned to each building by HPD.

columns.name: Number
columns.description: The House Number is the street number in the building’s address. E.g., the house number is ‘100’ in ‘100 Gold Street.’

columns.name: Street
columns.description: The Street Name is the name of the street in the building’s address. E.g., the street name is ‘Gold Street’ in ‘100 Gold Street.’

columns.name: Borough
columns.description: The Borough is the borough where the building is located.

columns.name: Postcode
columns.description: Zip code

columns.name: BBL
columns.description: The BBL (Borough, Block, and Lot) is a unique identifier for each tax lot in the City.

columns.name: BIN
columns.description: The BIN (Building Identification Number) is a unique identifier for each building in the City.

columns.name: Community Board
columns.description: The Community Board field indicates the New York City Community District where the building is located.

columns.name: Council District
columns.description: The Council District indicates the New York City Council District where the building is located.

columns.name: Census Tract
columns.description: The Census Tract indicates the 2010 U.S. Census Tract where the building is located.

columns.name: NTA - Neighborhood Tabulation Area
columns.description: The Neighborhood Tabulation Area indicates the New York City Neighborhood Tabulation Area where the building is located.

columns.name: Latitude
columns.description: The Latitude and Longitude specify the location of the property on the earth’s surface. The coordinates provided are an estimate of the location based on the street segment and address range.

columns.name: Longitude
columns.description: The Latitude and Longitude specify the location of the property on the earth’s surface. The coordinates provided are an estimate of the location based on the street segment and address range.

columns.name: Latitude (Internal)
columns.description: The Latitude (Internal) and Longitude (Internal) specify the location of the property on the earth’s surface. The coordinates provided are of the internal centroid derived from the tax lot.

columns.name: Longitude (Internal)
columns.description: The Latitude (Internal) and Longitude (Internal) specify the location of the property on the earth’s surface. The coordinates provided are of the internal centroid derived from the tax lot.

columns.name: Building Completion Date
columns.description: The Building Completion Date is the date the building was completed. The field is blank if the building has not completed.

columns.name: Reporting Construction Type
columns.description: The Reporting Construction Type field indicates whether the building is categorized as ‘new construction’ or ‘preservation’ in Housing New York statistics. Note that some preservation projects included here may not actually involve construction, because they extend the project’s regulatory restrictions but do not require rehabilitation.

columns.name: Extended Affordability Only
columns.description: The Extended Affordability Only field indicates whether the project is considered to be Extended Affordability. An extended affordability project involves no construction, but secures an extended or new regulatory agreement. All extended affordability projects have a ‘reporting construction type’ of ‘preservation.’

columns.name: Prevailing Wage Status
columns.description: The Prevailing Wage Status field indicates whether the project is subject to prevailing wage requirements, such as Davis Bacon.

columns.name: Extremely Low Income Units
columns.description: Extremely Low Income Units are units with rents that are affordable to households earning 0 to 30% of the area median income (AMI).

columns.name: Very Low Income Units
columns.description: Very Low Income Units are units with rents that are affordable to households earning 31 to 50% of the area median income (AMI).

columns.name: Low Income Units
columns.description: Low Income Units are units with rents that are affordable to households earning 51 to 80% of the area median income (AMI).

columns.name: Moderate Income Units
columns.description: Moderate Income Units are units with rents that are affordable to households earning 81 to 120% of the area median income (AMI).

columns.name: Middle Income Units
columns.description: Middle Income Units are units with rents that are affordable to households earning 121 to 165% of the area median income (AMI).

columns.name: Other Income Units
columns.description: Other Units are units reserved for building superintendents.

columns.name: Studio Units
columns.description: Studio Units are units with 0-bedrooms.

columns.name: 1-BR Units
columns.description: 1-BR Units are units with 1-bedroom.

columns.name: 2-BR Units
columns.description: 2-BR Units are units with 2-bedrooms.

columns.name: 3-BR Units
columns.description: 3-BR Units are units with 3-bedrooms.

columns.name: 4-BR Units
columns.description: 4-BR Units are units with 4-bedrooms.

columns.name: 5-BR Units
columns.description: 5-BR Units are units with 5-bedrooms.

columns.name: 6-BR+ Units
columns.description: 6-BR+ Units are units with 6-bedrooms or more.

columns.name: Unknown-BR Units
columns.description: Unknown-BR Units are units with an unknown number of bedrooms.

columns.name: Counted Rental Units
columns.description: Counted Rental Units are the units in the building, counted toward the Housing New York plan, where assistance has been provided to landlords in exchange for a requirement for affordable units.

columns.name: Counted Homeownership Units
columns.description: Counted Homeownership Units are the units in the building, counted toward the Housing New York Plan, where assistance has been provided directly to homeowners.

columns.name: All Counted Units
columns.description: The Counted Units field indicates the total number of affordable units, counted towards the Housing New York plan, that are in the building.

columns.name: Total Units
columns.description: The Total Units field indicates the total number of units, affordable and market rate, in each building.
